{This was the penultimate round of a tournament at the Marshall club and my
student Elliott Liu needed one point from his final two games to achieve his
second IM norm. We decided not to try and draw both. Instead, we opted to go
all out for wins in both, hoping for a single win, which he achieved in this
game.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. g3 {In this game we examine the
g1-knight's development to e2, rather than f3. The positions flow with a
reversed King's Indian flair, which suits Elliott perfectly, since he plays
the KID as Black. --- QUESTION: What is the difference with the knight on e2?
--- ANSWER: The difference is his unfettered kingside pawns are free to roam
forward. Also it's much easier to break a ...Bg4 pin when the knight nests on
e2.} Nf6 5. Bg2 Bg4 ({Alternatively,} 5... c6 6. h3 $5 Bf5 7. Nf3 h6 8. d3 e6
9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Rb1 a5 12. a3 Na6 13. Bf4 Qd8 14. Qe2 {and Black
equalized, A.Miltner-S.Tiviakov, Vienna 2009.}) 6. Nge2 c6 7. h3 Bxe2 {As
usual, Black is agreeable to the bishop for knight swap.} 8. Qxe2 e6 9. d3 Nbd7
10. O-O Be7 11. f4 {Playing it in KID style, with kingside pawn expansion.} O-O
{QUESTION: Didn't Black just castle into an attack?} ({ANSWER: Black's
kingside fortress isn't so easy to crack, but if you carry such concerns you
can try the more risky} 11... O-O-O $5 {. Be warned, White attacks quickly in
such positions with a prepared b4 and b5.}) 12. Bd2 Rfe8 13. Rae1 a5 14. g4
Qd4+ $6 {The queen chases a subsidiary afterthought. I don't understand the
GM's idea behind this move, which looks like a pure waste of time. ---
QUESTION: What would you suggest?} ({ANSWER: Either} 14... Nf8 {, adding
defenders}) ({or} 14... Bd8 {, rerouting the bishop to a more active diagonal.}
) 15. Kh1 g6 $6 {The beginning of an overly ambitious plan. Black decides that
he, not White, will do the attacking!} 16. a3 {This move is to prepare Be3 at
some timely point. "If I play Be3 without a3, Black may respond with the
annoying ...Qb4" writes Elliott.} Qb6 17. Nd1 $1 {Triple purpose: 1. Defending
b2. --- 2. Transferring an attacker to the kingside. --- 3. Clearing c3 for
his bishop.} h5 $6 {A decision which may cut the black king's life expectancy
short. Some people just have a predilection for confrontation. This is a
dangerous neighbourhood and it's the middle of the night, but realize this:
When an (attacking) addict's need arises, he must score his drug, or suffer
withdrawal agonies.} ({Elliott writes: "Way too aggressive. I was shocked by
this move, and it is a mistake. All along my opponent was planning to go after
my king when I thought I was the one trying to kill his!} 17... Bf8 {-g7 would
have been thematic and a lot better for Black as it would have been very
difficult for me to crack his fortress."}) 18. Bf3 hxg4 19. hxg4 Bc5 $5 {Still
in attack mode. The bishop indicates he won't participate in the defence. ---
QUESTION: What do you suggest?} ({ANSWER: I would add a defender with} 19...
Bf8 {.}) 20. Kg2 e5 $6 {Logical yet incorrect. --- QUESTION: Doesn't Black
follow the principle: Counter in the centre when attacked on the wing? ---
ANSWER: This is the intention, but the trouble is White simply bypasses and
the centre doesn't open.} 21. f5 gxf5 22. g5 $1 {Elliott writes: "This is the
move Palermo must have missed, but this pawn sacrifice is what I had been
planning all along. In fact, I think it is the only move in the position!" ---
QUESTION: Why not just recapture on f5?} ({ANSWER: On} 22. gxf5 $2 {Black
responds with} Kf8 $1 {intending ...Ke7, when it may be White's king who gets
hammered.}) 22... Nh7 ({Otherwise,} 22... Nd5 23. Be4 $3 {, and if} fxe4 24.
Qh5 {threatening f7 and also Rh1. Black is helpless.}) 23. Bh5 $1 {The bishop
skirts the edges of civilization.} f4 {EXERCISE (combination alert): White has
a method of obliterating Black's defences. How?} 24. Qg4 ({ANSWER: This is
okay, but White had} 24. Bxf4 $3 exf4 25. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 26. Qh5+ Kg8 27. Qg6+
Kh8 28. Rxe8+ {.}) 24... Ndf8 25. Bc3 {The bishop sulks, remaining hidden in
the shadows, biding time until the moment of retribution.} ({However, the
moment was now if White had found} 25. Bxf4 $3 exf4 26. Bxf7+ $1 {. Some
positions are so chaotic, so atonal, that their complexity overwhelms our puny
mental grasp. After} Kxf7 27. Qxf4+ Kg8 28. Qf7+ Kh8 29. Rxe8 Rxe8 30. Qxe8 Qc7
31. Rf7 {White has a winning attack.}) 25... Qc7 26. Qf5 $1 {Notice how
White's exposed yet perfectly safe king witnesses the proceedings with
